</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="362" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="17" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,512,536]" pageId="17" pageNumber="362">Remarks</emphasis>
. Newly erected, morphologically similar genus consisting of nine medium to large, marine whiprays previously placed in 
<taxonomicName box="[383,506,549,572]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Himantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="362" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[383,506,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="362">Himantura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The group contains at least three new species that are presently being described by the authors and their associates. Molecular analyses have divided the group into two subgroups; one containing largely black-spotted and/or white-spotted whiprays (gerrardi-complex), and another of largely plain-coloured whiprays (pastinacoides-complex) (see 
<figureCitation box="[595,662,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1873,1895]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dasyatidae (subfamily Urogymninae). Topology and branch lengths resulting from a constrained Maximum" pageId="17" pageNumber="362">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
